Lifting interest rates tends to increase the value of a nationâs money, as investors arrive seeking higher returns. But markets pushed down the value of the British pound against both the dollar and the euro following the central bankâs action, an apparent reflection of worry about Britainâs economy and its trade with Europe.
The clock is ticking toward a March 2019 deadline for negotiations between Britain and the European Union over their future dealings. So far, talks have produced a surplus of bitter recrimination and meager sign of an agreement.
Uncertainty is already exacting a price. Nearly half of Britainâs exports are sold within the European Union, a stream of cars, liquor and pharmaceuticals that could confront tariffs absent a completed trade deal. As the markets factor in the prospect of diminished trade across the English Channel, they have pushed down the value of the pound by nearly 15 percent against the euro since last yearâs Brexit vote.
